metadata.name: EcoPatterns #98
metadata.description:
This project is an invitation to see nature as an inspiring source through its complex and elegant patterns. The structures of a leaf, the symmetry of a flower, or the harmonious multicolored combinations can be inexhaustible resources for the mind of a generative artist eager to reproduce so much beauty around them.
Made entirely in p5.js

metadata.name: Platonics #33
metadata.description:
A response to being buffeted by forces outside of our control. Platonics sought to find order, control and solace in the Platonic solids. Instead it found beauty and intrigue in the emergent chaos that can arise from even the simplest systems.

Its building blocks are the five Platonic solids. Forms which have fascinated humanity for thousands of years. Their title comes from the philosophy of Plato, who equated each of the solids with a classical element.

Platonics arranges these forms in a series of geometric layouts, with varying density and randomness. At one extreme we see tidy radial circles consisting of a single solid. At the other, packed pentagons consisting of jumbled solids give rise to Escher-esque compositions which hold near infinite variety, variety enhanced by a range of pens and colours that draw and fill those solids.

This relationship between order and disorder is at the heart of Platonics. The collection seeks to show how they are not so far removed from one another ‚Äì and how we might embrace them both. It also aims to give collectors a behind the scenes look at how generative compositions can be constructed.

The geometric proof that there are only five convex regular polyhedra (the Platonic solids) states that at each vertex of the solid the angles between adjacent sides must be less than 360 degrees. This amount less than 360 degrees is known as the defect angle.

It is from this geometric proof that the collection size and pricing for Platonics is derived. There will be 360 Platonics sold via a Dutch auction priced according to the defect angles of the five Platonic solids: 180 > 120 > 90 > 60 > 36.

https://www.phaust.art/platonics

----------

Competition: Submit your favourite previews via Twitter to win a free mint and print.

Prints: Free gallery-grade, signed A3 prints for the first 18 mints.

Live: Press ‚ÄòS‚Äô to save in hi-res or append '&size=#' to the URL for custom height.

Info: Original artwork by Phaust. Winter 2023. London / Brighton. Made with p5js.

metadata.name: Sketches of the Departure #214
metadata.description:
Just like "Greetings From Habitable Zones" this piece is influenced by 70s retro poster aesthetics, Impressionism (colors) and the infinite vastness of space.
The palette consists of 11 carefully chosen colors which can occur randomly in every part of the piece.

Features:
 - Newborn rate / cocoon count
 - Probability of arrival / fleet size
 - Propulsion type
 - Fuel consumption

///
Click for audio.
Press "s" in live view to save a png of your sketch.

The music was written and recorded on April 4th, 2020 on a Tascam 4-track tape recorder.

///
Created with p5.js

Generative artwork by pxlshrd
Twitter: @pxlshrd

metadata.description:
NATURAL 02 are generative loops and animated pieces creating a fullscreen visual based on a noise with a painting effect.‚Ä®It‚Äôs the second part of a collection call NATURAL.
The size, position and frequency of trails are generated for each token, along with the color theme. ‚Ä®Movements are generated by a flow based on a noise, is different for each views.
You can press spacebar to stop the animation.

‚Ä®Features :
	- Generated grid between 14 and 50 cols and rows
	- 2 kind of shapes (circles and squares), it can be full of squares or circles üëÄ
	- The shapes can be stroked or filled : sometimes it can be full stroked or filled üëÄ
	- Background color :  color randomly get from 1 of 134 color themes

Created by Quentin Hocd√©, in Brussels (Belgium).

metadata.name: Less is More #25
metadata.description:
In this case, we tried to avoid abstract expressionist tendencies by removing personal scenarios.
Take a step back and let's create a geometrical work that intentionally avoids the usual conventional elements, focusing mainly on logic and physics concepts such as mathematical expansions and gravity.
In fact, we based our work and expression on the basis of simplicity and simple methods, as well as free from the usual philosophical or pseudo-philosophical complexity, and we concluded that by using simple geometric shapes, color, form, and material can be achieved in a pure manner.
Made by p5.js
press 's' to save original size
